### Sport

Further information: [Sport in Tonga](/Sport_in_Tonga)

#### Rugby union

[Rugby union](/Rugby_union) holds an almost sacred status as the national sport of Tonga, [106] a passion that unites the island nation. The [national team](/Tonga_national_rugby_union_team), affectionately known as the ʻIkale Tahi (or Sea Eagles), has achieved remarkable success on the international stage, consistently punching above its weight. Tonga has proudly participated in six [Rugby World Cups](/Rugby_World_Cup) since the inaugural tournament in [1987](/1987_Rugby_World_Cup). The [2007](/2007_Rugby_World_Cup) and [2011 Rugby World Cups](/2011_Rugby_World_Cup) stand out as Tonga's most successful campaigns to date. In both tournaments, the ʻIkale Tahi secured two victories out of four matches, placing them in a strong contention for the quarterfinals, a truly impressive feat for a nation of its size. During the 2007 Rugby World Cup, Tonga made a spectacular start, winning its first two matches against the [USA](/United_States_national_rugby_union_team) (25–15) and [Samoa](/Samoa_national_rugby_union_team) (19–15). They then came agonizingly close to upsetting the eventual tournament winners, the formidable South African [Springboks](/Springboks), ultimately losing by a narrow margin of 30–25. A subsequent defeat by [England](/England_National_Rugby_Union_Team) (36–20) in their final pool game, however, extinguished their hopes of advancing to the knockout stages. Nevertheless, by securing a commendable third place in their pool, behind South Africa and England, Tonga earned automatic qualification for the 2011 Rugby World Cup in [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), a testament to their improved performance. In [Pool A](/2011_Rugby_World_Cup_Pool_A) of the 2011 tournament, Tonga once again demonstrated their prowess, defeating both [Japan](/Japan_national_rugby_union_team) (31–18) and, in a stunning upset, the 5th-ranked [France](/France_national_rugby_union_team) (19–14) in the later pool stages. [107] However, a heavy defeat by the host nation [All Blacks](/All_Blacks) in the tournament's opener (41–10) and a subsequent tight loss to [Canada](/Canada_national_rugby_union_team) (25–20) meant that Tonga narrowly missed out on a quarterfinal berth to France, primarily due to bonus points and a superior points difference of 46.

Tonga's most impressive results prior to 2007 occurred in the [1995 Rugby World Cup](/1995_Rugby_World_Cup), where they triumphed over [Côte d'Ivoire](/Ivory_Coast_national_rugby_union_team) with a score of 29–11, and in [1999](/1999_Rugby_World_Cup), when they secured a victory against [Italy](/Italy_national_rugby_union_team) (28–25), although they suffered a heavy defeat against [England](/England_National_Rugby_Union_Team) (101–10) while playing with only 14 men. Before every match, the Tongan team performs the stirring [Ikale Tahi war dance](/Kailao), or Sipi Tau, a powerful form of [Kailao](/Kailao) that embodies their warrior spirit and cultural heritage. Historically, Tonga competed in the [Pacific Tri-Nations](/Pacific_Tri-Nations) against [Samoa](/Samoa) and [Fiji](/Fiji), a competition that has since been replaced by the more inclusive [World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup](/World_Rugby_Pacific_Nations_Cup), which now also features [Japan](/Japan), [Canada](/Canada), and the [United States](/United_States). At the club level, domestic competitions include the [Datec Cup Provincial Championship](/Datec_Cup_Provincial_Championship) and the regional [Pacific Rugby Cup](/Pacific_Rugby_Cup). Rugby union in Tonga is governed by the [Tonga Rugby Football Union](/Tonga_Rugby_Football_Union), which was formerly a member of the [Pacific Islands Rugby Alliance](/Pacific_Islands_Rugby_Alliance) and contributed players to the [Pacific Islanders rugby union team](/Pacific_Islanders_rugby_union_team) before its disbandment in 2009.

A remarkable number of players of Tongan descent have achieved international acclaim, playing for some of the world's most prestigious national teams, including the [All Blacks](/All_Blacks) of [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) or the [Wallabies](/Wallabies) of [Australia](/Australia). Notable figures include legends like [Jonah Lomu](/Jonah_Lomu) and [Israel Folau](/Israel_Folau), alongside talents such as [Viliami "William" ʻOfahengaue](/Viliami_Ofahengaue), [Malakai Fekitoa](/Malakai_Fekitoa), [Ben Afeaki](/Ben_Afeaki), [Charles Piutau](/Charles_Piutau), [Frank Halai](/Frank_Halai), [Sekope Kepu](/Sekope_Kepu), [George Smith](/George_Smith_(rugby_union)), [Wycliff Palu](/Cliff_Palu), [Sitaleki Timani](/Sitaleki_Timani), [Salesi Ma'afu](/Salesi_Ma%27afu), [Anthony](/Anthony_Fainga%27a) and [Saia Fainga'a](/Saia_Fainga%27a), [Mark Gerrard](/Mark_Gerrard), [Cooper Vuna](/Cooper_Vuna), [Doug Howlett](/Doug_Howlett), [Toutai Kefu](/Toutai_Kefu), and [Tatafu Polota-Nau](/Tatafu_Polota-Nau). The reach of Tongan talent extends even further: [British and Irish Lion](/British_and_Irish_Lions) and Welsh international player [Taulupe "Toby" Faletau](/Taulupe_Faletau) is Tongan-born and the son of former Tongan international [Kuli Faletau](/Kuli_Faletau). Moreover, Taulupe's cousins, the England international players [Billy](/Billy_Vunipola) and [Mako Vunipola](/Mako_Vunipola) (who is also a [British and Irish Lion](/British_and_Irish_Lion)), are the sons of former Tonga rugby captain [Fe'ao Vunipola](/Fe%27ao_Vunipola). Rugby's popularity is deeply embedded in the nation's schools, with students from institutions such as Tonga College and [Tupou College](/Tupou_College) regularly being offered coveted scholarships to continue their rugby and academic careers in [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), [Australia](/Australia), and [Japan](/Japan), further cementing Tonga's legacy in the sport.

#### Rugby league

The Tongan rugby league team

[Rugby league](/Rugby_league) has also enjoyed considerable success within Tonga, carving out its own significant niche alongside rugby union. The Tongan national rugby league team made its debut at a [Rugby League World Cup](/Rugby_League_World_Cup) in the [1995](/1995_Rugby_League_World_Cup) edition, where, despite being eliminated in the first stage, they put up a valiant effort, narrowly losing to the formidable [New Zealand](/New_Zealand_national_rugby_league_team) team. Since then, Tonga has become a consistent presence, appearing in every subsequent Rugby League World Cup tournament, demonstrating their growing commitment and prowess in the sport. In the [2008 Rugby League World Cup](/2008_Rugby_League_World_Cup), Tonga recorded impressive victories against both [Ireland](/Ireland_national_rugby_league_team) and [Scotland](/Scotland_national_rugby_league_team), showcasing their ability to compete effectively on the international stage.

A pivotal moment in Tongan rugby league history occurred just before the [2017 World Cup](/2017_Rugby_League_World_Cup), when several high-profile players, led by the influential figures of [Jason Taumalolo](/Jason_Taumalolo) and [Andrew Fifita](/Andrew_Fifita), made the courageous and widely publicized decision to defect from their respective Tier 1 nations (such as [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand)) to represent their nation of heritage, Tonga. This act of profound loyalty galvanized the team and the nation, leading to an electrifying victory against New Zealand in Hamilton at [Waikato Stadium](/Waikato_Stadium) on 11 November during that tournament, a moment that resonated deeply across the Pacific. The national team has since continued its upward trajectory, achieving further significant victories against powerhouse teams like [Great Britain](/Great_Britain_national_rugby_league_team) and even the world number one ranked [Australia](/Australia), solidifying their status as a genuine force in international rugby league. In addition to the national team's success, numerous players of Tongan descent have achieved considerable renown in the Australian [National Rugby League](/National_Rugby_League) (NRL) competition, a testament to the deep talent pool within the Tongan community. These include stars such as [Jason Taumalolo](/Jason_Taumalolo), [Israel Folau](/Israel_Folau), [Tyson Frizell](/Tyson_Frizell), [Tevita Pangai Junior](/Tevita_Pangai_Junior), [Konrad Hurrell](/Konrad_Hurrell), [David Fusitua](/David_Fusitua), [Tuimoala Lolohea](/Tuimoala_Lolohea), [Sio Siua Taukeiaho](/Sio_Siua_Taukeiaho), [Jorge Taufua](/Jorge_Taufua), [William Hopoate](/William_Hopoate), [Andrew Fifita](/Andrew_Fifita), [Ben Murdoch-Masila](/Ben_Murdoch-Masila), [Felise Kaufusi](/Felise_Kaufusi), [Willie Mason](/Willie_Mason), [Manu Vatuvei](/Manu_Vatuvei), [Brent Kite](/Brent_Kite), [Fuifui Moimoi](/Fuifui_Moimoi), [Willie Tonga](/Willie_Tonga), [Anthony Tupou](/Anthony_Tupou), [Antonio Kaufusi](/Antonio_Kaufusi), [Michael Jennings](/Michael_Jennings_(rugby_league)), [Tony Williams](/Tony_Williams_(rugby_league)), and [Feleti Mateo](/Feleti_Mateo). Subsequently, some Tongan rugby league players have also established successful careers in the [Super League](/Super_League) in Europe, such as Antonio Kaufusi, further broadening the international impact of Tongan talent in the sport. [108]

#### Olympics

Main article: [Tonga at the Olympics](/Tonga_at_the_Olympics)

Beyond the dominant rugby codes, Tonga has also proudly produced athletes who have competed on the global stage at both the Summer and Winter Olympics, showcasing a diverse range of athletic talent. Tonga's only Olympic medal to date was achieved at the [1996 Summer Olympics](/1996_Summer_Olympics) held in Atlanta, where the formidable [Paea Wolfgramm](/Paea_Wolfgramm) earned a silver medal in the [super heavyweight](/Boxing_at_the_1996_Summer_Olympics_%E2%80%93_Super_heavyweight) boxing category, a moment of immense national pride. More recently, one iconic athlete, [Pita Taufatofua](/Pita_Taufatofua), gained international recognition for his memorable appearances, notably attending the [2018 Winter Olympics](/2018_Winter_Olympics) in Pyeongchang, South Korea, where he competed in cross-country skiing, famously appearing shirtless in traditional Tongan attire during the opening ceremonies, a powerful symbol of his nation's spirit.

#### American football

American football, while not indigenous to the islands, has nonetheless seen a remarkable number of Tongans achieve professional success in the [National Football League](/National_Football_League) (NFL). The sheer physical prowess and disciplined nature often found in Tongan athletes lend themselves well to the demanding sport. This impressive list of NFL players of Tongan descent includes [Naufahu Tahi](/Naufahu_Tahi), [Tuineau Alipate](/Tuineau_Alipate), [Sione Takitaki](/Sione_Takitaki), [Spencer Folau](/Spencer_Folau), [Lakei Heimuli](/Lakei_Heimuli), [Steve Kaufusi](/Steve_Kaufusi), [Ma'ake Kemoeatu](/Ma%27ake_Kemoeatu), [Deuce Lutui](/Deuce_Lutui), [Siupeli Malamala](/Siupeli_Malamala), [Tim Manoa](/Tim_Manoa), [Stan Mataele](/Stan_Mataele), [Vili Maumau](/Vili_Maumau), [Alfred Pupunu](/Alfred_Pupunu), [Vai Sikahema](/Vai_Sikahema), [Star Lotulelei](/Star_Lotulelei), [Kalani Sitake](/Kalani_Sitake), [Vita Vea](/Vita_Vea), [Talanoa Hufanga](/Talanoa_Hufanga), [Peter Tuipulotu](/Peter_Tuipulotu), [Marlon Tuipulotu](/Marlon_Tuipulotu), and [Tuli Tuipulotu](/Tuli_Tuipulotu). [109] Their achievements underscore the global reach of American football and the significant contributions of Tongan athletes to the sport.

### Media

The media landscape in Tonga, while relatively small, is diverse, offering various avenues for information dissemination and public discourse. These outlets play a crucial role in shaping public opinion and keeping citizens informed, despite occasional controversies surrounding press freedom.

*   *Matangi Tonga* – An online newspaper that provides news and analysis, often serving as a key source of information for both local and international audiences.
*   *Taimi o Tonga* (*Times of Tonga*) – A newspaper that has historically been considered controversial, [according to whom?] often due to its critical stance on government actions and its role in political debates.
*   *Keleʻa* – Another newspaper, known for its pro-democracy leanings and its role in advocating for political reform.
*   *Talaki* – A newspaper contributing to the daily news and information flow within the kingdom.
*   *Kalonikali* – Yet another newspaper, part of the traditional print media in Tonga.
*   *Tauʻataina* – A newspaper that adds to the plurality of voices in the Tongan media.
*   *Kakalu* – A newspaper, further enriching the local news offerings.
*   [Tonga Broadcasting Commission](/Tonga_Broadcasting_Commission) – This is the primary public broadcaster in Tonga, encompassing a range of television and radio services:
    *   [Television Tonga](/Television_Tonga) and [Television Tonga 2](/Television_Tonga_2) – The national television channels, providing visual news, entertainment, and public service programming.
    *   [Radio Tonga](/Radio_Tonga) 1 and [Radio Tonga](/Radio_Tonga) 2 – Kool 90FM – The national radio stations, offering news, music, and cultural content across the airwaves.
    *   [103FM](/Radio_Tonga) – An additional radio frequency, further expanding broadcasting options for the Tongan public.

### Contemporary Tongan art

The past decade has witnessed a significant surge in the emergence of contemporary Tongan artists, [when?] a vibrant cultural renaissance that is increasingly gaining international recognition. The majority of these talented individuals are based in [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), where a strong Tongan diaspora provides a fertile ground for artistic expression and development. Tanya Edwards, for instance, masterfully works with *ngatu* (traditional bark cloths), transforming this ancient medium into compelling contemporary statements. [110] Artists such as [Benjamin Work](/Benjamin_Work), [Telly Tuita](/Telly_Tuita), and [Sione Monū](/Sione_Mon%C5%AB) have achieved widespread acclaim, with their works extensively exhibited internationally, bringing Tongan artistic perspectives to a global audience. [111] [112] [113] Closer to home, Sēmisi Fetokai Potauaine has made a monumental contribution to public art, constructing a striking five-storey Tongan sculpture in central [Christchurch](/Christchurch), [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), a powerful symbol of Tongan identity in an urban landscape. [114] In a testament to the growing prominence of this movement, [Bergman Gallery](/Bergman_Gallery) hosted a significant exhibition titled "Tukufakaholo, Tongan Contemporary" in [Auckland](/Auckland), [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), in 2023. This exhibition proudly showcased the diverse talents and innovative approaches of eight prominent Tongan artists, further cementing their place in the contemporary art world. [115]

